---
import SeriesHeroImage from '../../assets/k3s-hero.png';
import Layout from '../../layouts/BlogPost.astro';

// The published parts, newest thinking first. As a roadmap item ships, move it
// up here and give it an href. Keep `href` off anything unwritten so the hub
// never points at a 404.
const published = [
	{
		n: 1,
		href: '/blog/kubernetes-first-app-k3s-single-node/',
		title: 'Deploy an app on a single k3s node and watch it heal',
		blurb:
			'The whole core loop on one node: deploy nginx, kill a Pod and watch a replacement appear, scale it, roll out an update with no downtime, then tear it all down. Both manifests are inline, commented line by line.',
	},
	{
		n: 2,
		href: '/blog/kubernetes-configmaps-secrets-k3s/',
		title: 'ConfigMaps and Secrets: config and passwords out of your image',
		blurb:
			'Pull settings, a whole web page, and a password out of the image and into the cluster, as env vars and mounted files, then change them live with no rebuild. Plus the base64 gotcha that trips everyone.',
	},
];

const upcoming = [
	{ name: 'Labels and Namespaces', blurb: 'Organize and isolate groups of objects.' },
	{ name: 'Volumes', blurb: 'Keep data alive when Pods disappear.' },
	{
		name: 'Health probes',
		blurb: 'Liveness and readiness, so Kubernetes knows when your app is actually OK.',
	},
	{ name: 'Ingress', blurb: 'Route real outside web traffic to your Services.' },
];
---

<Layout
	title="Kubernetes on k3s: a hands-on series"
	description="Learn Kubernetes the way it sticks, by running it. A hands-on k3s series on one cheap node: your first Deployment and the reconciliation loop, then config, storage, health checks, and Ingress. Real commands, no cloud bill."
	kind="page"
	showDate={false}
	heroImage={SeriesHeroImage}
>
	<p class="whoami"><span class="prompt">~/$</span> kubectl get series</p>

	<p>
		This is a running series on learning Kubernetes the way I actually learned it: by
		putting <a href="https://k3s.io">k3s</a> on a spare box and breaking things until the
		model clicked. No managed cloud, no monthly bill, one node you could otherwise use as a
		doorstop. Every part is a short, self-contained tutorial you can run start to finish in
		an evening.
	</p>

	<p>
		If you take one thing from the whole series, take this: <strong
			>you declare the state you want, and Kubernetes works to make reality match it,
			forever.</strong
		> Deployments, scaling, self-healing, rolling updates, the lot. They are all variations on
		that one loop. Once you have watched it happen with your own eyes, the pile of unfamiliar
		nouns turns into a handful of settings on the same idea.
	</p>

	<h2>The parts</h2>

	<ol class="parts">
		{
			published.map((p) => (
				<li class="part done">
					<span class="badge live">Part {p.n} · live</span>
					<a href={p.href}>{p.title}</a>
					<p>{p.blurb}</p>
				</li>
			))
		}
		{
			upcoming.map((p, i) => (
				<li class="part next">
					<span class="badge">Part {published.length + i + 1} · in progress</span>
					<span class="name">{p.name}</span>
					<p>{p.blurb}</p>
				</li>
			))
		}
	</ol>

	<p class="closing">
		I write these as I go, so this page is the map. The next part lands here first, so if the
		series is useful to you, this is the URL worth bookmarking.
	</p>
</Layout>

<style>
	.whoami {
		font-family: var(--font-mono);
		color: var(--sys-dim);
		margin-bottom: 1.5em;
	}
	.whoami .prompt {
		color: var(--sys-fg);
		font-weight: 700;
	}
	.parts {
		list-style: none;
		margin: 1.5em 0;
		padding: 0;
	}
	.part {
		border: 1px solid var(--sys-dim);
		border-left: 3px solid var(--sys-dim);
		padding: 1em 1.2em;
		margin: 0 0 1em;
	}
	.part.done {
		border-left-color: var(--sys-fg);
	}
	.part .badge {
		display: inline-block;
		font-family: var(--font-mono);
		font-size: 0.75rem;
		text-transform: uppercase;
		letter-spacing: 0.06em;
		color: var(--sys-dim);
		margin-bottom: 0.4em;
	}
	.part .badge.live {
		color: var(--sys-fg);
	}
	.part a,
	.part .name {
		display: block;
		font-family: var(--font-mono);
		font-weight: 700;
		font-size: 1.05rem;
		line-height: 1.3;
	}
	.part .name {
		color: var(--sys-dim);
	}
	.part p {
		margin: 0.4em 0 0;
		font-size: 0.95rem;
		color: var(--sys-text);
	}
	.part.next p {
		color: rgb(var(--gray));
	}
	.closing {
		margin-top: 1.5em;
	}
</style>
